      "answer": "Let me analyze this project scheduling problem. The context contains a simple task dependency graph. I need to calculate the minimum completion time with unlimited parallelism.\n```repl\n# Parse the tasks and calculate minimum completion time\nimport re\n\n# Extract task information\ntasks = {}\nfor line in context.split('\\n'):\n    match = re.match(r'(\\w+):\\s*(\\d+)\\s*days,\\s*deps=\\[([^\\]]*)\\]', line)\n    if match:\n        name = match.group(1)\n        duration = int(match.group(2))\n        deps_str = match.group(3)\n        deps = [d.strip() for d in deps_str.split(',') if d.strip()]\n        tasks[name] = {'duration': duration, 'deps': deps}\n\nprint(\"Tasks:\")\nfor name, info in tasks.items():\n    print(f\"  {name}: {info['duration']} days, depends on {info['deps']}\")\n\n# Calculate earliest finish time for each task\ndef calc_earliest_finish(task_name, tasks, memo={}):\n    if task_name in memo:\n        return memo[task_name]\n    \n    task = tasks[task_name]\n    if not task['deps']:\n        earliest_start = 0\n    else:\n        earliest_start = max(calc_earliest_finish(dep, tasks, memo) for dep in task['deps'])\n    \n    earliest_finish = earliest_start + task['duration']\n    memo[task_name] = earliest_finish\n    return earliest_finish\n\n# Find the task that finishes last\nmemo = {}\nmax_finish = 0\nfor task_name in tasks:\n    finish = calc_earliest_finish(task_name, tasks, memo)\n    print(f\"Task {task_name} finishes at day {finish}\")\n    max_finish = max(max_finish, finish)\n\nprint(f\"\\nMinimum project duration: {max_finish} days\")\n```",
